docs.abstract: Washington’s crackdown on Big Tech is coming for Apple.
docs.snippet: Washington’s crackdown on Big Tech is coming for Apple.
docs.lead_paragraph: Last week, the Justice Department took aim at Apple, accusing the company of violating competition laws with practices intended to keep customers reliant on their iPhones.

headline.main: The United States vs. the iPhone

byline.original: By Sabrina Tavernise, David McCabe, Carlos Prieto, Mooj Zadie, Eric Krupke, Summer Thomad, Liz O. Baylen, Brad Fisher, Dan Powell, Marion Lozano, Diane Wong, Elisheba Ittoop and Alyssa Moxley

docs.abstract: For years, Apple, Google, Meta and others operated unfettered. But new laws and regulations have finally compelled them to make major shifts to their products and businesses.
docs.snippet: For years, Apple, Google, Meta and others operated unfettered. But new laws and regulations have finally compelled them to make major shifts to their products and businesses.
docs.lead_paragraph: By Thursday, Google will have changed how it displays certain search results. Microsoft will no longer have Windows customers use its Bing internet search tool by default. And Apple will give iPhone and iPad users access to rival app stores and payment systems for the first time.

headline.main: Forced to Change: Tech Giants Bow to Global Onslaught of Rules
headline.print_headline: Big Tech Bows to Force of Law

byline.original: By Adam Satariano and David McCabe

docs.abstract: The Justice Department’s lawsuit against the iPhone maker pushes the boundaries of competition rules. Some experts say that may make winning more difficult.
docs.snippet: The Justice Department’s lawsuit against the iPhone maker pushes the boundaries of competition rules. Some experts say that may make winning more difficult.
docs.lead_paragraph: With its antitrust lawsuit against Apple, the Biden administration has joined a growing list of regulators taking on the iPhone giant. But the Justice Department is taking a more ambitious approach than the others by aiming at the company’s tight control of the iPhone ecosystem, which officials say hurts consumers and developers while producing giant profits.

headline.main: How the Fight Against Apple Could Redefine Antitrust Law

byline.original: By Andrew Ross Sorkin, Ravi Mattu, Bernhard Warner, Sarah Kessler, Michael J. de la Merced, Lauren Hirsch and Ephrat Livni

docs.abstract: After losing two complaints before the U.S. International Trade Commission, Apple has stepped up its lobbying to change the agency’s practices.
docs.snippet: After losing two complaints before the U.S. International Trade Commission, Apple has stepped up its lobbying to change the agency’s practices.
docs.lead_paragraph: Over the past decade, some of Apple’s biggest regulatory headaches have come from a little-known federal agency called the U.S. International Trade Commission. The agency’s patent judges have found Apple guilty of appropriating innovations in smartphones, semiconductors and smartwatches. And recently, they forced Apple to remove a health feature from Apple Watches.

headline.main: Apple Keeps Losing Patent Cases. Its Solution: Rewrite the Rules.
headline.print_headline: Apple Aims To Rewrite Patent Rules

docs.abstract: What is lost when journaling moves into the cloud?
docs.snippet: What is lost when journaling moves into the cloud?
docs.lead_paragraph: After a routine iPhone update, a new Journal app recently appeared. Intrigued, I tapped it, which led to the instruction “Enable journaling suggestions.” If I agreed, my phone promised to give prompts like “Take a moment to write about something special in your life you’ve been taking for granted” and “Take a look around you and take a picture of something you’ve overlooked. What do you notice about it?”

headline.main: An Analog Library of All the Lives I’ve Lived
headline.print_headline: A Library Of the Lives I’ve Lived

docs.abstract: Prosecutors compare their new fight against Apple to the seminal case against Windows in the 1990s.
docs.snippet: Prosecutors compare their new fight against Apple to the seminal case against Windows in the 1990s.
docs.lead_paragraph: Impeding innovation. Reducing consumer choice. Extending dominance to other markets.

headline.main: The Second Coming of the Microsoft Antitrust Battle?
headline.print_headline: Is Apple Antitrust Suit An Echo of Microsoft?

byline.original: By Michael J. de la Merced, Sarah Kessler and Ravi Mattu

docs.abstract: The lawsuit caps years of regulatory scrutiny of Apple’s wildly popular suite of devices and services, which have fueled its growth into a nearly $3 trillion public company.
docs.snippet: The lawsuit caps years of regulatory scrutiny of Apple’s wildly popular suite of devices and services, which have fueled its growth into a nearly $3 trillion public company.
docs.lead_paragraph: The federal government’s aggressive crackdown on Big Tech expanded on Thursday to include an antitrust lawsuit by the Justice Department against Apple, one of the world’s best-known and most valuable companies.

headline.main: U.S. Sues Apple, Accusing It of Maintaining an iPhone Monopoly
headline.print_headline: U.S. Suing Apple, Seeing Monopoly Built on Iphones

byline.original: By David McCabe and Tripp Mickle

docs.abstract: The inquiries signal the bloc’s intention to tightly enforce sweeping new competition rules that took effect this month.
docs.snippet: The inquiries signal the bloc’s intention to tightly enforce sweeping new competition rules that took effect this month.
docs.lead_paragraph: Alphabet, Apple and Meta were told by European Union regulators on Monday that they were under investigation for a range of potential violations of the region’s new competition law.

headline.main: E.U. Takes Aim at Alphabet, Apple and Meta in Wide-Ranging Investigations
headline.print_headline: E.U. Targets Tech Giants Over Rules On Fairness

byline.original: By Adam Satariano and Tripp Mickle

docs.abstract: Apple said it would appeal the penalty, the latest in a series of regulatory setbacks for the tech giant.
docs.snippet: Apple said it would appeal the penalty, the latest in a series of regulatory setbacks for the tech giant.
docs.lead_paragraph: Apple on Monday was fined 1.8 billion euros ($1.95 billion) by European Union regulators for thwarting competition among music streaming rivals, a severe punishment levied against the tech giant in a long-simmering battle over the powerful role it plays as gatekeeper of the App Store.

headline.main: Apple Fined $2 Billion by E.U. for Using App Store to Thwart Competition
headline.print_headline: Apple Fined $2 Billion By E.U. Over Store

byline.original: By Tripp Mickle and Adam Satariano

docs.abstract: A partnership would extend the long relationship between the companies that has helped deliver everything from maps to search on Apple’s devices.
docs.snippet: A partnership would extend the long relationship between the companies that has helped deliver everything from maps to search on Apple’s devices.
docs.lead_paragraph: Apple is in discussions with Google about using the search giant’s generative artificial intelligence model called Gemini for its next iPhone, as the company races to embrace a technology that has upended the tech industry.

headline.main: Apple and Google Are Discussing a Deal to Bring Generative A.I. to iPhones
headline.print_headline: Apple Talking to Google About A.I. for iPhone

byline.original: By Tripp Mickle, Nico Grant and Brian X. Chen
